                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" id="affectation_sng_1" hclass="sense"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">behaviour or an action that is not natural or sincere and that is often intended to impress other people</span></span><ul class="examples" hclass="examples" htag="ul"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">His little affectations irritated her.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">Kay has no affectation at all.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">He raised his eyebrows with an affectation of surprise <span class="gloss" htag="span" hclass="gloss">(= pretending to be surprised)</span>.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">He speaks clearly and without affectation.</span></li></ul><div class="collapse" htag="div" hclass="collapse"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="affectation_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">mid 16th cent.: from Latin <span class="ei">affectatio(n-)</span>, from the verb <span class="ei">affectare</span> ‘aim at’, frequentative of <span class="ei">afficere</span> ‘work on, influence’, from <span class="ei">ad-</span> ‘at, to’ + <span class="ei">facere</span> ‘do’.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
